TRIP

PURPOSE
Check external numeric telemetry streams in CI.

Programs emit key=value or "key value" lines. trip checks them against rules,
emits tab-separated events, and exits nonzero when a configured level fires.

USAGE
make
./some_test_or_benchmark | ./trip -r rules.trip

Rules can come from atlas:

atlas rules examples/rover/telemetry.atlas > rules.trip
program | trip -r rules.trip

RULES
Format:

key op number level event_id
key stale duration level event_id

Examples:

frame.ms              > 16.6    warn   frame.slow
queue.depth           > 1000    error  queue.backpressure
heartbeat             stale 5s  error  heartbeat.missing
temperature           > 80      warn   temperature.high cooldown 10s

Operators:

> >= < <= == != stale

Levels:

info warn error

INPUT
Accepted forms:

frame.ms=18.7
queue.depth 1402

OUTPUT
Tab-separated events on stdout:

warn	frame.slow	frame.ms	>	16.600000000000001	18.699999999999999

Exit status:

0  no failing rule
1  failing info/warn/error rule, depending on --fail-on
2  invalid input, rule, or argument

LIBRARY
The rule parser and evaluator live in libctc. trip is intentionally just the
stdin parser and process exit policy around ctc_sample().

